<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06100132 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06100132 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Mrs. Hurley  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  OBITUARY; MEMORIAL; SERVICE; PALO-ALTO; EDUCATION; PROFESSIONAL  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A memorial service will be conducted April 19 for Elsie Murtagh Hurley, 78, aformer reading teacher and instructor with the Learning Assistance Program.;   Mrs. Hurley died April 1 of a stroke at Stanford University Medical Centerafter being stricken while attending a fashion show at a Palo Alto hotel.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  ELSIE M. HURLEY, 78, EX-READING TEACHER  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Mrs. Hurley was born in Jamaica, N.Y. During World War II, she commandedcompanies in the Women's Army Auxiliary Corps in Indiana and later in theTroop Carrier Command at Fairfield-Suisun (now Travis) Air Force Base nearVacaville.;    While living in Arlington, Va., she obtained a master's degreein education. She taught orthopedically handicapped people for one year andbecame a reading teacher at several schools. She then became a schoolprincipal and began teaching extension courses in reading at George WashingtonUniversity.;    In 1964, Mrs. Hurley moved to Palo Alto and became a teacherin the Learning Assistance Program. She became a deputy to the head of theprogram and managed the program while the director was on leave.;    Mrs.Hurley also taught reading courses at Cabrillo Community College and waspresident of the Council on Reading in Santa Clara County.;    Mrs. Hurley wasa former president of the Mount Hamilton branch of the Republican Women'sFederation and was active in the medical auxiliary at The Villages. She was afounder and president of the Evergreen Valley chapter of the CaliforniaRetired Teachers Association. She volunteered with the Council on Aging ofSanta Clara County and the Independent Aging Program.;    Mrs. Hurley issurvived by her husband, William J. Hurley of San Jose; daughters PatriciaHays of Rhode Island and Kathleen Hayden of Kalispell, Mont.; a brother,Raymond Murtagh of Long Island, N.Y.; a sister, Mary Pasternak of Saugerties,N.Y.; and five grandchildren.;    The memorial service will begin at 10:30a.m. April 19, which would have been Mrs. Hurley's 79th birthday, at TheVillages, 5000 Cribari Lane, San Jose. Mrs. Hurley's cremated remains will bescattered in Monterey Bay.  </TEXT><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910409  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  3B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  335  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday April 9, 199100100132,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>